'''Wooden Coffin''' (木棺, Mokkan) refers to a coffin made from {{ill|wood|ja|木材|12=draft|12=draft}} used to enclose [[:en:remains|remains]].
== Overview == In addition to wooden coffins, there are {{ill|Clay Coffins|ja|甕棺|12=draft|12=draft}}, [[:en:Jar burial|urn coffins]], {{ill|sekkan|lt=stone coffins|ja|石棺|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|ceramic coffins|ja|陶棺|1=Ceramic Coffins|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|lacquer coffins|ja|乾漆棺|1=Kanshitsu coffin|12=draft|12=draft}}.
Due to the availability of wood, ease of processing, and the custom of cremation, wooden coffins have been continuously used in Japan since ancient times.
Wooden coffins are classified into two types: '''assembled wooden coffins''' (組合式木棺, Kumiawase-shiki Mokkan), made by joining planks, and '''carved wooden coffins''' (刳抜式木棺, Kurinuki-shiki Mokkan), made by carving a single piece of wood into a body and lid.
Assembled wooden coffins were introduced to northern Kyushu in the late {{ill|Jōmon period|ja|縄文時代|12=draft|12=draft}} alongside rice cultivation and continue to be used today. Carved wooden coffins, including {{ill|split bamboo-shaped wooden coffins|ja|割竹形木棺|1=Waritakegata Mokkan|12=draft|12=draft}}, were introduced from the continent in the late {{ill|Yayoi period|ja|弥生時代|12=draft|12=draft}} and were widely used in the early {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, later replaced by box-shaped coffins during the later Kofun period.
Both assembled and carved wooden coffins are '''reclining coffins''' (寝棺, Nekan), used to lay the deceased flat or sideways. However, starting in the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft|12=draft}}, '''seated coffins''' (座棺, Zakan) for burying the deceased in a sitting posture also appeared.<ref>Sitting burials were also observed in the mid-to-late Yayoi period in regions like Kibi and Hokkaido.</ref>
Seated coffins include circular and rectangular variants. Circular coffins are known as "early coffins" or "barrel coffins," while rectangular ones are referred to as "standing coffins" or "box coffins."
== Types == === Assembled Wooden Coffins === Typically box-shaped, these first appeared in western Japan during the late Jōmon period and developed further in the Yayoi period and beyond.
=== Carved Wooden Coffins === * '''[[Waritakegata Mokkan|Split bamboo-shaped coffins]]''': Small versions appeared in the late Yayoi period. * '''[[Funagata Sekkan|Boat-shaped coffins]]''': Seen during the Yayoi and Kofun periods.
== References == <references />
== Suggested Readings == * Tanaka Taku and Sahara Makoto, eds., *Nihon Kōkogaku Jiten* (Dictionary of Japanese Archaeology), Sanseidō, 2003, ISBN 978-4-385-15835-8. * Nagahara Keiji (supervising editor), Ishigami Eiichi et al., *Iwanami Nihonshi Jiten* (Iwanami Japanese History Dictionary), Iwanami Shoten, 1999, ISBN 978-4-00-080093-8.
== Related Articles == * {{ill|Kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Coffin|ja|棺|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|sekkan|ja|石棺|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Stone coffin tombs in Yayoi burial practices|ja|弥生時代の墓制#石棺墓|12=draft|12=draft}} * {{ill|Wooden coffin tombs in Yayoi burial practices|ja|弥生時代の墓制#木棺墓|12=draft|12=draft}}
{{Japanese-history-stub}}
